#                                                              ↑ N+1!
```

**Count queries in tests with Hibernate statistics:**
```java
@Autowired EntityManager em;

@Test
void findAll_noNPlusOne() {
    // Enable statistics:
    SessionFactory sf = em.getEntityManagerFactory()
        .unwrap(SessionFactory.class);
    sf.getStatistics().setStatisticsEnabled(true);
    sf.getStatistics().clear();

    // Execute the query:
    orderService.getAllOrderDtos();

    // Assert query count:
    long queryCount = sf.getStatistics().getQueryExecutionCount();
    assertEquals(1, queryCount, "Should execute exactly 1 query, not N+1");
}

concept_explanation.fix_join_fetch:
**Fix 1: JOIN FETCH — the most reliable solution:**

```java
// In OrderRepository:

// Bad (N+1):
List<Order> findAll();
// SELECT * FROM orders → then N lazy selects for each user

// Good (1 query):
@Query("SELECT o FROM Order o JOIN FETCH o.user JOIN FETCH o.restaurant")
List<Order> findAllWithDetails();
// SELECT o.*, u.*, r.* FROM orders o
// JOIN users u ON o.user_id = u.id
// JOIN restaurants r ON o.restaurant_id = r.id
// → 1 query, all data in one round trip

// With filtering (JOIN FETCH + WHERE):
@Query("SELECT o FROM Order o JOIN FETCH o.user WHERE o.status = :status")
List<Order> findByStatusWithUser(@Param("status") String status);

// With Optional:
@Query("SELECT o FROM Order o JOIN FETCH o.user WHERE o.id = :id")
Optional<Order> findByIdWithUser(@Param("id") String id);
```

**JOIN FETCH with @OneToMany — the count issue:**
```java
@Entity class Restaurant {
    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "restaurant", fetch = FetchType.LAZY)
    private List<Order> orders;
}

// JOIN FETCH on @OneToMany creates a Cartesian product:
@Query("SELECT r FROM Restaurant r JOIN FETCH r.orders")
List<Restaurant> findAllWithOrders();
// If 10 restaurants each have 100 orders:
// Result set has 1000 rows (10 × 100)
// Hibernate deduplicates, but huge memory use!

// Fix for @OneToMany: use DISTINCT or @BatchSize
@Query("SELECT DISTINCT r FROM Restaurant r JOIN FETCH r.orders")
List<Restaurant> findAllWithOrdersDistinct();
```

concept_explanation.fix_entity_graph:
**Fix 2: @EntityGraph — no JPQL needed:**

```java
import org.springframework.data.jpa.repository.EntityGraph;

// In repository:
@EntityGraph(attributePaths = {"user", "restaurant"})
List<Order> findAll();
// Hibernate generates: SELECT o.*, u.*, r.*
//   FROM orders o LEFT JOIN users u ON o.user_id = u.id
//                 LEFT JOIN restaurants r ON o.restaurant_id = r.id

// For specific queries:
@EntityGraph(attributePaths = {"user"})
List<Order> findByStatus(String status);

// Named entity graph (defined on @Entity):
@NamedEntityGraph(
    name = "Order.withDetails",
    attributeNodes = {
        @NamedAttributeNode("user"),
        @NamedAttributeNode("restaurant")
    }
)
@Entity
public class Order { ... }

// Use named graph in repository:
@EntityGraph("Order.withDetails")
List<Order> findByCreatedAtAfter(LocalDateTime since);
```

**Fix 3: @BatchSize — middle ground for collections:**
```java
@Entity class Restaurant {
    @OneToMany(mappedBy = "restaurant")
    @BatchSize(size = 30)  // Hibernate batches 30 loads at once
    private List<Order> orders;
}
// Instead of N queries (one per restaurant),
// Hibernate does: SELECT * FROM orders WHERE restaurant_id IN (id1, id2, ..., id30)
// N/30 queries instead of N queries
// Good when full JOIN FETCH creates too large a result set
```

